725492f-b.title: Queens: 58th Street - Maspeth Avenue
725492f-b.text:
58th Street, east side, from Maspeth Ave (left), to 57th Drive.
(right), as seen across Maspeth Ave. in the foreground. Note the
Long Island right of way across front of picture. The buildings in
their order, from left to right, are the Queens Tavern, the Maurice
house, and St. Saviours Protestant Episcopal Church. This is a set
of two views.
September 1929.
View 2: March 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
MAY BE REPRODUCED.

725493f-a.title: Queens: 58th Street - Maspeth Avenue
725493f-a.text:
58th Street (foreground), south from Maspeth Ave. to 57th Drive,
showing from left to right, the Queens Head Tavern, at the corner;
the Maurice house, in the center; and St. Saviours Protestant Episcopal
Church. 58th Street was originally Flushing Ave.,(also Creek Street)
near the Queens Tavern,but it was discontinued at this point where it
curved,and 58th Street was extended in a straight line.
March 1925.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
MAY BE REPRODUCED.

727360f-a.title: Queens: Maspeth Avenue - 58th Street
727360f-a.text:
Maspeth Ave. (car thereon), at, adjoining and east of the
N.E. corner of 58th Street (right, also foreground), showing at
the corner the Queens Head Tavern. See other views for more data.
March 1923.
Eumene L. Armbruster Collection.
MAY BE REPRODUCED.

727361f-b.title: Queens: Maspeth Avenue - 58th Street
727361f-b.text:
Maspeth Ave. (center view), eastward from 58th Street (right),
viewed from the Long Island Railroad right of way seen in the fore-
ground. At the S.E. corner of Maspeth Ave. and 58th Street (right
foreground) is the former Queen's Head Tavern. This is a set of
two views.
January 1924.
View 2: 1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

727363f-a.title: Queens: Maspeth Avenue - 58th Place
727363f-a.text:
Maspeth Ave. (formerly No. 165), south side, between 58th Place
and 58th Street, showing in a set of three views the John Van Cott house
from 1852-1891. In 1929 it was occupied by the Maspeth Garment Corporation.
1922.
Views 2 \& 3: March 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
MAY BE REPRODUCED.
